                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="58767" author="rjrjr@google.com" created="Mon, 4 Oct 2010 11:48:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;James, I&apos;m pretty sure this is how things work out of the box, but can you confirm?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="58856" author="jtyrrell" created="Wed, 6 Oct 2010 07:25:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I can&apos;t confirm definitively, but I am very sure a blanket transaction is not configured per request. I think this is so locking DB connections are not held for a longer period of time than necessary.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t see why the referenced example wouldn&apos;t work. A single EntityManager exists per request which should mean that the retrieved address and the address belonging to Person are one and the same. So the modification made should be persisted when calling persist (which is annotated with @Transactional) as the modifications made to the persistence context are meant to be flushed to the DB at the end of a successful transaction.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="58866" author="rjrjr@google.com" created="Wed, 6 Oct 2010 09:38:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;That&apos;s the important thing &#8212; the single EM. Sorry for my incompetent phrasing.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
